TNP quenches the fluorescence of GQDs by an energy transfer mechanism, and thus, a linear calibration may be obtained between the quenched fluorescence intensity and the concentration of TNP. Consequently, TNP may be analyzed quantitatively. In this context, a series of TNP solutions with different concentrations were prepared and added, respectively to the GQD solutions (final concentration, 0.05mgmL−1); the fluorescence intensity of these solutions was measured immediately in sequence, and at 450nm it decreased with increasing concentration of TNP (Fig. 4
                        ), moreover, the spectra red shifted gradually, which was attributed to the partial overlap between emission of GQDs and absorption of the quencher. The quenching ratio was linear in the TNP concentration range of 0.1 to 15μmolL−1. The limit of detection (LOD) was 0.091μmolL−1 (S/N
                        =3) and the correlation coefficient was 99.8% (inset 1, Fig. 4). The relative standard deviation was 7.1% for the determination of the 10μmolL−1 TNP (n
                        =3); these figures of merit suggest that the novel analytical method has satisfactory sensitivity, linearity and reproducibility. As compared with some traditional methods for analysis of TNP or other nitrobenzene compounds (Table 1
                        ), this method showed some advantages, especially its good sensitivity. Moreover, compared with some other reported methods based on metal nanoparticles (MNPs) or metal quantum dots (MQDs) sensing for the analysis of TNP or TNT (Table 2
                        ), the LOD of this method for detection of TNP is similar to MNPs or MQDs. Usually, MNPs and MQDs have relatively higher sensitivity than carbon nanomaterials and other non-metal nanomaterials. Taking into consideration the fact that GQDs are environmentally friendly and harmless when penetrating cells or organisms, it seems that GQDs perform better than MNPs and MQDs sensors.
